body:
## Purpose
This javascript object is written to allow a developer to make ajax calls for any project without having to write custom response handlers for every project. With just a single ajax call you can update multiple parts of a page regardless if you updating code or just content. In fact you can update code blocks on one portion of a page, just content on another portion, and even form fields on a page all with a single ajax call.

The magic is accomplished by using a standardized JSON model. This JSON model holds key:value pairs where the key is the ID of an element on a page to update and the value portion is the code or content that will be placed into the page.

Here is an example:  

    {
        "head": {
		"status": 200,
		"data": {
			"code": 400,
			"message": "message that can be displayed in the browser, useful when an error occurs"
		}
	},
	"body": {
		"update": {
			"html": [
				{
					"id": "mainTitle",
					"value": "Title Was Updated"
				},
				{
					"id": "mainPara",
					"value": "This paragraph was updated and and it now contains some <strong>HTML</strong>."
				}
			]
		},
		"replace": {
			"forms": [
				{
					"id": "name",
					"value": "Michael Turnwall"
				}
			],
			"content": [
				{
					"id": "updateMe",
					"value": "1234567890"
				}
			]
		}
        }
    }

## Usage
Using the ajax object is very simple. Everything is done with just one function call.

    Digi.ajax.getData(url, [method], [parameters]);

**url**: this is the URL you are making the Ajax call to.  
**method** [optional]: this is your method of choice which is usually GET or POST. Get is the default  
**parameters** [optional]: this is an object literal so you can pass data to the server.

## Requirements
Right now jQuery 1.3+ is required. A future version will make the object framework free so you can use it with your framework of choice.
